## Executive Summary

Switzerland’s Swiss Agency for Development and Cooperation (SDC) is a
key humanitarian donor with a total 2025 funding of \$105.5 million,
demonstrating significant earmarking across eight regions, with priority
given to a few high-need areas. SDC exhibits a rising geographic reach,
supporting an average of 16 countries annually, indicative of strategic
expansion. Despite funding volatility and lower transaction frequency
compared to top donors, SDC’s substantial earmarked share (38%) reflects
focused investment in targeted programs. Fundraisers should align
proposals with SDC’s regional priorities and multi-country engagement,
emphasizing adaptability to shifting allocations and advocating for more
consistent, larger disbursements to enhance program continuity.

## Volatility

The funding data for Switzerland’s Swiss Agency for Development and
Cooperation (SDC) reveals significant volatility and lower transaction
volumes compared to other top donors. Over 131 recorded transactions,
SDC averages 1.2 million USD per transaction, with about 43.7
transactions per year. In contrast, the benchmark of the top 10 other
donors shows a much higher average transaction value of 2.9 million USD
and a larger frequency of approximately 371.3 transactions annually.
This disparity highlights that SDC funding is both less frequent and
lower in amount, which may affect program continuity and scale in
supported regions. The transaction values exhibit substantial variance,
with some individual disbursements reaching up to 18 million USD, but
the majority cluster below 1 million USD. The timeline of transactions
spans from early 2023 up to late 2025, indicating ongoing funding
commitments but with noticeable fluctuations in disbursement amounts.
For proposal design and fundraising strategies, it is crucial to
consider this volatility and comparatively lower transaction volume as
potential limits to planning and impact. Enhancing funding
predictability and increasing transaction frequency could improve
operational stability. Identifying gaps or underfunded periods through
this data can help advocate for more consistent and substantial
contributions from SDC or encourage partnership with other donors to
leverage complementary funds.
